wcg_strategy: I try not to think too long as thinking too much makes you stumble and blank out, so I just associate the first or second thing that pops into my mind, and I've been reading the news a lot the past week so I'm sure there's quite an amount of some sad, anxious, kinda depressing themes. This is exactly why I'm trying to read a lot less news and just focus more on my life. But word association is a lot of fun, I wouldn't mind doing more of that. I just tie anything into it that's somewhat relatable. For example, eagle, falcon, they eat small game, but I thought of worms, nutrition, so I just kept rolling with it.
guess_experiment: It's trying to measure your ability to recall a story after experiencing fast-paced stimuli. I'm not exactly sure. This one's kind of a tricky one. I'm sure I'm probably wrong, but even if I'm a little right that would be cool.
wcg_diff_general: For some reason, it felt like it was harder to come up with words the second time. I don't know if that's related to the story or not.
volition_explanation: Actually, I treated the exercise almost completely separate from the story, because it's so different. But it was in the back of my mind which I feel like slowed me down a little, and made me stop and pause longer. At the same time, I don't feel like it affected me too much because... Actually, no, yeah, I slowed down, but it wasn't because of the story I don't feel like. I'm not sure exactly. It definitely took up a bit of my brain capacity to reason and think on the fly, be creative. A bit of a distraction at the very least.
wcg_diff_explanation: I did feel a little more anxious, a little more agitated, I felt like I'm being rushed more. I also felt like the pauses of empty thinking, empty thoughts, etc. were longer because I could notice a difference in the length of my pauses alone. I'm not sure how much it affected me though, but it did for sure. This is a very interesting study that I haven't really encountered a similar one to. Thank you for the study.
open_box: This was a very interesting experience. I've long suspected that if you're focusing on something else, or multiple tasks, your critical brain function slows down as you're working with limited capacity. It's like trying to read a technical document at work when you're tired or on low sleep, your brain just doesn't register it the same way, and you might need to reread a few times to memorize it or even understand it well enough.   When we are distracted, it's similar to like being low sleep, in my opinion. I feel like things that grab our attention, our distractions, are usurping away the limited brain function we have. The limited amount of brain "energy" we have for that day, you know, it's a limited resource. Anyway, to tie it back with the study, definitely noticed a change after reading the story and doing the word game again. Which is ironic actually, because usually the second time you'd do a game it would become a lot easier.   Thanks again for the study. That was interesting.
